   {
    "id": "c7-plan-loop",
    "title": "Big task, one small piece at a time",
    "blurb": "Each step sees only what it asked for, never the whole dossier. Cut a fact a step needed, and it refuses instead of guessing.",
    "cmd": "node examples/bootstrap/c7-plan-loop.js",
    "out": "\n  A BIG TASK, DONE ONE SMALL PIECE AT A TIME\n  ──────────────────────────────────────────\n  Give a model a whole dossier and ask a deep question, and it drowns. So the task is cut\n  into steps — and each step is shown ONLY what it actually asked for. Not the dossier.\n  Not its neighbours. Just its own inputs.\n\n  1.  Four figures to work out from a report. THIS is the entire prompt each step received —\n         not a summary of it, the actual string the engine handed over:\n\n     ┌─ the \"revenue\" step was sent ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n     │ GOAL Analyze the annual report · (root) · PRODUCE L0\n     └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n     ┌─ the \"costs\" step was sent ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n     │ GOAL Analyze the annual report · (root) · PRODUCE L1\n     └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n     ┌─ the \"margin\" step was sent ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n     │ GOAL Analyze the annual report · USE L0=913,L1=400 · PRODUCE L2\n     └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n     ┌─ the \"marginPct\" step was sent ───────────────────────────────────────────────────\n     │ GOAL Analyze the annual report · USE L2=513,L0=913 · PRODUCE L3\n     └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n       ✓ each one is one line long. Nobody ever saw the whole dossier — that is the entire trick\n         (USE = the values it asked for, already worked out. PRODUCE = the one thing it owes.)\n       the answer              costs=400;margin=513;marginPct=56;revenue=913\n\n  2.  Now we take away a figure that one of the steps needs. What does it do?\n       ✗ it REFUSES that step, by name — it does not guess a plausible number\n       ✓ and the answer carries a visible hole where the figure should be\n       ✓ the model was never even asked. It was stopped before it could invent\n         (a framework would run the step anyway and let the model make something up.)\n\n  3.  Last one: hand it a sloppy plan — steps in the wrong order, one asked for twice.\n       ✓ the duplicate is noticed and dropped — the work is not done twice\n       ✓ the order sorts itself out, and the right answer comes back anyway\n\n  BOOTSTRAP OK — every step sees only what it asked for — and a step missing a fact refuses instead of inventing one."
   },
   {
    "id": "c9-critical-mind",
    "title": "A critic that will not take your word",
    "blurb": "Nothing enters the argument without real evidence behind it — including the model's own ideas. Too close to call says so.",
    "cmd": "node examples/bootstrap/c9-critical-mind.js",
    "out": "\n  A CRITIC THAT WILL NOT TAKE ANYONE'S WORD FOR IT — INCLUDING ITS OWN\n  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n  Ask a model to weigh both sides of a question and it will happily produce a confident,\n  well-written answer built on points it made up. This one only lets a point into the\n  argument if real evidence in front of it actually says so.\n\n  1.  \"Should we go fully remote?\" — with 6 real arguments handed to it, 4 for and 2 against.\n\n     ┌─ WE SENT THE MODEL ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n     │ Question: Should we go fully remote?\n     │ PRO statements:\n     │ p1: nobody commutes any more — that is an hour a day back for most of the team\n     │ p2: we would not renew the office lease, which is our second largest fixed cost\n     │ p3: we could hire from anywhere instead of within an hour of this building\n     │ p4: the last internal survey came back strongly in favour of staying remote\n     │ Name the 2 main DISTINCT points of view these statements support. Reply 2 lines, each: V: <short name of the viewpoint>\n     ├─ IT REPLIED ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n     │ V: saves real money\n     │ V: better for the people who work here\n     └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n       → so the model reads the FOR arguments and names what they are really claiming\n\n     ┌─ WE SENT THE MODEL ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n     │ Question: Should we go fully remote?\n     │ Point of view (PRO): saves real money\n     │ Statements:\n     │ p1: nobody commutes any more — that is an hour a day back for most of the team\n     │ p2: we would not renew the office lease, which is our second largest fixed cost\n     │ p3: we could hire from anywhere instead of within an hour of this building\n     │ p4: the last internal survey came back strongly in favour of staying remote\n     │ c1: the two juniors who joined last year took visibly longer to get up to speed\n     │ c2: decisions that used to take a corridor conversation now take three days of messages\n     │ Which statements GENUINELY make this exact point (not merely the same side)? Cite AT MOST 2. Reply ONE line, format: cites: ids_or_NONE\n     ├─ IT REPLIED ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n     │ cites: p1, p2\n     └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n       → and for each claim, we make it point at the evidence. This is the gate: no citation, no entry\n       → [PRO] \"saves real money\"  — backed by 2 of the arguments given\n       → [CON] \"juniors learn slower\"  — backed by 1 of the arguments given\n       ✓ every point in the argument points at the evidence that carries it\n\n  2.  Two points it thought of, but could NOT back up:\n       → \"better for the people who work here\" — nothing in the evidence actually said this\n       → \"decisions get slower\" — nothing in the evidence actually said this\n       ✓ they stay visibly unproven. They are not quietly dropped, and not quietly asserted\n\n  3.  Then the model proposes two new ideas of its own. Here it judges itself:\n       → \"it widens who we can hire\" — accepted: 2 unused arguments back it\n       ✗ its second idea was REFUSED — only 1 argument was left to back it, and 1 is not enough\n       ✓ the model does not get special treatment. Its own ideas face the same bar\n\n  4.  So which side wins?\n       for                     2 points that survived\n       against                 1 point that survived\n       ✗ it refuses to call it. One point apart is too close, so it says so plainly\n         (a model asked to pick a winner here picks one, confidently, about half the time.)\n\n  5.  And if you hand it almost no evidence at all — two lonely arguments?\n       ✗ it refuses to even start, and says why: there is not enough here to reason about\n       model calls spent       0 — it refused BEFORE costing you anything\n\n  BOOTSTRAP OK — nothing gets in without evidence — not even the model's own ideas — and too close to call says so."
   },
   {
    "id": "f3-task-memory",
    "title": "A finished task that un-finishes itself",
    "blurb": "A number turns out to be wrong. The work that used it re-does itself for free — or, if nothing can be recomputed, un-ticks itself and tells you why.",
    "cmd": "node examples/bootstrap/f3-task-memory.js",
    "out": "\n  A FINISHED TASK THAT UN-FINISHES ITSELF\n  ───────────────────────────────────────\n  Every to-do list in the world only ever ticks boxes. But what happens when the number a\n  finished task was built on turns out to be wrong? The box stays ticked, and the answer\n  quietly rots. Watch this one un-tick itself instead.\n\n  1.  A report says revenue 913, costs 400. Two tasks compute the margin, then the margin %.\n       margin                  513  (913 − 400)\n       margin %                56 %\n       ✓ both tasks are ticked off on your own to-do list\n\n  2.  An erratum arrives: revenue was not 913, it was 1000. We change that one number.\n       margin                  600  — updated itself\n       margin %                60 %  — and so did the one built on top of it\n       ✓ both re-did themselves. No model was called. Nobody was told to recompute\n       ✓ nothing to un-tick: the answers simply followed the correction\n\n  3.  Worse news: the costs figure is withdrawn entirely. Nothing can be recomputed now.\n       ✗ the margin is now a HOLE — not the stale 600 it used to say\n       ✗ and the margin %, which was built on it, went with it\n\n  4.  And here is what lands on YOUR to-do list, unprompted:\n       → re-open \"margin\" — premise drifted: revenue,costs (rev 9)\n       → re-open \"pct\" — premise drifted: r_margin,revenue (rev 10)\n       ✓ both tasks un-ticked themselves — including the one that only depended on it indirectly\n       ✓ and each says WHY, and as of when. Not just a status flip\n       ✓ ask again and it says nothing new — it only ever tells you what CHANGED\n\n  BOOTSTRAP OK — correct a number and the work redoes itself for free; withdraw one and the finished task un-finishes itself, with the reason."
   },
   {
    "id": "f7-substrate",
    "title": "Undo, for reasoning",
    "blurb": "Every settled state is a version you can diff and roll back to — rules included. And a sandbox stays a sandbox until you merge it.",
    "cmd": "node examples/bootstrap/f7-substrate.js",
    "out": "\n  UNDO — FOR REASONING\n  ────────────────────\n  Your code has version control. The thinking your model does has none: it happens, and\n  then it is gone. Here every settled state is a version you can compare and go back to —\n  and there is no model involved anywhere in this file. This part is just the engine.\n\n  1.  A rule: an order over 100 counts as large. One order of 120 arrives.\n       ✓ flagged large — and that state is now a version. You did not ask for it, it just is\n\n  2.  A second order arrives: 40. What changed between the two versions?\n       → appeared: an order of 40 — not flagged, it is under the line\n       ✓ the comparison names the thing that appeared, and hands you its details\n\n  3.  Someone raises the bar: large now means over 500. We change the RULE, not the data.\n       ✓ the 120 order stops being large, immediately — nothing was recomputed by hand\n  4.  That was a mistake. Undo.\n       ✓ the 120 order is large again — because THE RULE came back too, not just the data\n         (this is the part people miss: the rules are data here, so they version like data.\n          Undo a step where you also changed a rule, and the rule change is undone with it.)\n\n  5.  Try something risky in a sandbox: a draft order of 900, off to one side.\n       ✓ the sandbox reasons with the same rules it inherited\n       ✓ and the main world cannot see it at all. Nothing leaked\n  6.  We like the result, so we bring back exactly one number from it — and only that.\n       brought back            900\n       ✓ nothing else crossed. You decide what comes back, and in what shape\n\n  BOOTSTRAP OK — every settled state is a version you can diff and undo — rules included — and a sandbox stays sealed until you choose what comes back."
   },
   {
    "id": "forge-stock",
    "title": "Where the certified know-how comes from",
    "blurb": "Turn a dataset with a right-answer checker into reusable method shapes — admitting nothing that is not provably right.",
    "cmd": "node examples/bootstrap/forge-stock.js",
    "out": "\n  WHERE THE CERTIFIED KNOW-HOW COMES FROM\n  ───────────────────────────────────────\n  A small model gets much better at a task when it is handed the SHAPE of a known-good\n  answer. But where do those shapes come from, and why would you trust them? They are\n  mined from a dataset that has a right-answer checker — and nothing gets in unproven.\n\n  1.  Three kinds of question, each with examples and a checker that knows the right answer.\n       kinds examined          3\n       kinds accepted          3 — each provably matches what the checker expects\n       wrong ones let in       0\n\n  2.  \"Zero wrong ones let in\" is easy to score if you let everything in. So it tests itself:\n       → a deliberately WRONG shape is offered to the gate, on purpose\n       ✓ rejected. So the zero above means something — the gate really does say no\n\n  3.  The accepted know-how is packed into one file you can hand to someone else.\n       ✓ a fresh machine loads all 3 back — it is not stuck where it was made\n\n  4.  And it ships with its paperwork, so you never have to take our word for it:\n       → what it was mined from  · demo-corpus\n       → what did the mining     · gold-forge (deterministic)\n       → every check, and its result · all 3 pass\n       → the fingerprint of the exact file it certifies · sha256 cfffac3c73f6652c…\n       ✓ the paperwork names the bytes. Paperwork that does not, certifies nothing\n\n  5.  One last piece of honesty: when a MODEL did the mining rather than a checker —\n       ✓ the paperwork says so, by name: \"some-local-gguf\"\n         (it never quietly claims the stricter checker did work a model actually did.)\n\n  BOOTSTRAP OK — nothing unproven gets in, the gate is tested against a deliberately wrong answer, and the paperwork names the exact file."
   }
